snippet.textDisplay:
Theory 1: It’s in the Raimi Universe

Rebuttal: While we do, in fact, see the suit from Sam Raimi’s Spider-Man trilogy in this trailer, Morbius is meant to exist in the same universe as Venom (2018). The Venom film cannot exist in the Raimi universe because a version of Venom and Eddie Brock are already in that universe. Therefore, Morbius does not take place in the Raimi universe.

Theory 2: It’s in an alternate universe

Rebuttal: Sony have been wanting to link their own movies to the MCU for a while now. They wanted Tom Holland to be in Venom but Marvel shot that down. The new contract stipulation from September may have allowed Sony to reference events in the MCU. The fact that Spider-Man has been dubbed a murderer as well as Vulture’s appearance heavily implies that Morbius and Venom are in the MCU.

I argue that there are two likely answers. First, the a set designer screwed up or is messing with us. Marvel puts fake elements in their trailers all the time, so it’s possible Sony is doing the same. Second, Sony doesn’t own the rights to use the Stark-enhanced suits because their origin is based on Iron Man. One may think that Sony could use the Night Monkey suit, but the general public of the MCU thinks that Night Monkey and Spider-Man are two different people. Therefore, Sony decided to give Spider-Man a new suit that is not Stark-enhanced. Spider-Man has been given a new suit in every MCU movie he has played a key role in.

In conclusion, Morbius and Venom are in the MCU because Venom already exists in the Raimi Universe, Sony wants to be part of the MCU and it doesn’t make sense for Spider-Man to be dubbed a murderer in any other context. The likely answers are that a production designer did something wrong or Sony simply doesn’t own the Stark-enhanced Spider-Man suits.

Thanks for reading!
